==Criticism==

===Accusations of Anglophobia===
Some critics of the SNP accuse the party of being [[Anglophobia|Anglophobic]]. As James Maxwell points out, such allegations have a long history in British politics, becoming particularly pronounced since the rise of the SNP in Labour's West of Scotland heartlands in the 1960s and 70s.<ref>http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/the-staggers/2012/04/scottish-labour-party-snp</ref>

During his time as a Liberal Democrat MSP, [[Jamie Stone]] was forced to apologise after calling the SNP "[[xenophobia|xenophobic]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/highlands_and_islands/10213416.stm|title=Lib Dem MSP Jamie Stone to quit Holyrood at election|date=2 June 2010|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> In 2000, the Labour Party claimed that two SNP MSPs were anti-[[English people|English]] after they "registered their support for Germany's [[FIFA World Cup hosts#2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 FIFA World Cup]] bid on its official website" which was then a rival to England's 2006 World Cup bid.<ref name="SNP's German support condemned">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/625090.stm |title=SNP's German support condemned |publisher=BBC News |date=30 January 2000 |accessdate=20 April 2010}}</ref> The SNP responded that they "have no position on where the World Cup is held" and that it was "silly to describe the website entry as anti-English".<ref name="SNP's German support condemned"/> More recently, former Conservative Prime Minister [[John Major]] and former Conservative Cabinet minister [[John Redwood]] have branded the SNP "anti-English".<ref>http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/political-news/redwood-snp-anti-english.17045479</ref>

The SNP have been quick to refute any suggestions of Anglophobia within the party. Former SNP MSP [[Ian McKee]] pointed out in a speech to the Scottish Parliament that, as an Englishman, he was evidence of there being no such anti-English feeling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/officialReports/meetingsParliament/or-07/sor1206-02.htm |title=The Scottish Parliament - Official Report |publisher=Scottish.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=20 April 2010}}</ref> Indeed, McKee was then one of seven SNP MSPs born in England.<ref name="news.bbc.co.uk">http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7342692.stm</ref> Other prominent English-born figures in the party include prospective MEP [[Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh]], [[Christine Grahame]] MSP, [[Stuart McMillan]] MSP, [[Nigel Don]] MSP, Cabinet Secretary for Education and Lifelong Learning [[Michael Russell (politician)|Mike Russell]], Cabinet Secretary for the Commonwealth Games, Sport, Equalities and Pensioners' Rights [[Shona Robison]] and the party's Westminster leader [[Angus Robertson]] MP.<ref name="news.bbc.co.uk"/>

In 2007/08, 6.7% of SNP members were found to have been born in England, "not far below the 8.1% recorded in the 2001 census for the population as a whole".<ref name="The Modern SNP 2009, p. 70">"The Modern SNP: From Protest to Power", edited by Gerry Hassan, Edinburgh University Press: Edinburgh, 2009, p. 70</ref> Nearly half - 47.2% - of the party reported having lived in England.<ref name="The Modern SNP 2009, p. 70"/>

The SNP's founder, [[R.B. Cunninghame Graham]] is famously quoted as saying: "The enemies of Scottish Nationalism are not the English, for they were ever a great and generous folk, quick to respond when justice calls. Our real enemies are among us, born without imagination."<ref name="BBC">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/radioscotland/2012/09/the-cause-a-history-of-scottis.shtml |title=The Cause: A History of Scottish Nationalism |publisher=BBC Radio Scotland |date=21 September 2012 |accessdate=21 May 2013}}</ref> Graham was, along with close friend [[Keir Hardie]], one of the founders<U+2014>indeed, the first president<U+2014>of the [[Scottish Labour Party]] in 1888.<ref name="BBC" /> The party's current leader, [[Alex Salmond]], told the ''Guardian'' newspaper in 2011 that he believed England to be "a great country" of which he was personally very fond.<ref>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rP0F2BeEQag</ref>

===Accusations of "cash for policies"===

The party has been criticised over a <U+00A3>500,000 donation from the [[social conservatism|socially conservative]] transport businessman [[Brian Souter]]. One month later, in April 2007, the SNP's commitment (made at the party's 2006 conference) to re-regulate the bus network was not included in their 2007 manifesto, although the SNP denies any direct link.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=539&id=621242007 |title=SNP under attack after bus U-turn |publisher=Business.scotsman.com |date= |accessdate=20 April 2010}}{{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref> Opposition politicians suggested that the donation and policy shift were linked and that it was a case of "cash for policies", although no official accusations have been made.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundayherald.com/news/heraldnews/display.var.1346656.0.snp_accused_of_dumping_bus_plan_to_please_millionaire_backer.php |title=SNP accused of dumping bus plan to please millionaire backer |publisher=Sundayherald.com |date=21 April 2007 |accessdate=20 April 2010}}{{dead link|date=June 2013}}</ref> In spite of Souter's strong opposition,<ref>http://www.christianstogether.net/Articles/287632/Christians_Together_in/Christian_Life/Christians_and_Politics/SNP_millionaire_supporters.aspx</ref> the SNP government moved to legalise same-sex marriage in Scotland. In February 2014, with the overwhelming backing of SNP MSPs, as well as cross-party support, the Scottish Parliament voted to approve the SNP government's plans.<ref>http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-25960225</ref>

Souter went on to make a further donation of <U+00A3>125,000 to the SNP, making him their single biggest donor at that time.<ref>{{cite web|last=Swanson |first=Ian |url=http://edinburghnews.scotsman.com/latestnews/SNP-faces-hovercraft-dustup.3719954.jp |title=SNP faces hovercraft dust-up |publisher=Edinburghnews.scotsman.com |date= |accessdate=20 April 2010}}</ref> Souter made approaches to the SNP government for a <U+00A3>3&nbsp;million subsidy for his company, [[Stagecoach Group|Stagecoach]], to develop a [[hovercraft]] service between [[Kirkcaldy]] and [[Portobello, Edinburgh|Portobello]] in Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|author=Paul Hutcheon |url=http://www.sundayherald.com/news/heraldnews/display.var.1807832.0.snp_donor_in_3_3m_hovercraft_subsidy_plea.php |title=SNP donor in <U+00A3>3.3m hovercraft subsidy plea |publisher=Sundayherald.com |date=3 November 2007 |accessdate=20 April 2010}}{{dead link|date=June 2013}}</ref> The service had already received subsidy from the previous Labour administration for the pilot scheme, but was put on hold pending "clarification" of the public sector's involvement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/7253201.stm |title=Scotland &#124; Edinburgh, East and Fife &#124; Row over Forth hovercraft freeze |publisher=BBC News |date=19 February 2008 |accessdate=20 April 2010}}</ref>

